Project: Wrangle and Analyze Data¶

A source for professional dog ratings, WeRateDogs' Twitter account is brought into focus in this project. Here, datasets pertaining to this Twitter account have been wrangled and analyzed to bring to light insights that are then visualized.

WeRateDogs can be viewed here :https://twitter.com/dog_rates

  • This project has two sections where section 1 is within this notebook. Section 1 is divided into two, data wrangling and data visualization.

Gathering Data: Twitter API¶

  • Use tweet_id from twitter archive to link with Twitter API and retrieve both fields

    1. Declare Twitter consumer API keys, access tokens, access secrets
    2. Using the tweet IDs in the WeRateDogs Twitter archive, query the Twitter API for each tweet's JSON data using Python's Tweepy library
    3. store each tweet's entire set of JSON data in a file called tweet_json.txt file
    4. Each tweet's JSON data should be written to its own line.
    5. read this .txt file line by line into a pandas DataFrame with (at minimum) tweet ID, retweet count, and favorite count
In [212]:

auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_secret)

api = tweepy.API(auth, wait_on_rate_limit=True, wait_on_rate_limit_notify=True)

# Using the tweet IDs in the WeRateDogs Twitter archive,
#  query the Twitter API for each tweet's JSON data using Python's Tweepy library

#   If the tweet json file does not exist, create it   
tweet_json_file = 'tweet_json.txt'
exists = os.path.isfile(tweet_json_file)
if exists:
    print('{} already exists, no need to build the file again.'.format(tweet_json_file)) 
else:
# below code retrieved from instructor notes (twitter-api.py)
    count = 0
    fails_dict = {}
    start = timer()
    # Save each tweet's returned JSON as a new line in a .txt file
    with open('tweet_json.txt', 'w') as outfile:
        # This loop will likely take 20-30 minutes to run because of Twitter's rate limit
        for tweet_id in tweet_ids:
            count += 1
            print(str(count) + ": " + str(tweet_id))
            try:
                tweet = api.get_status(tweet_id, tweet_mode='extended')
                print("Success")
                json.dump(tweet._json, outfile)
                outfile.write('\n')
            except tweepy.TweepError as e:
                print("Fail")
                fails_dict[tweet_id] = e
                pass
    end = timer()
    print("Time taken to process loop: {} minutes".format((end - start)/60))
    print(fails_dict)

  • twitter_archive table

Tidiness "A standard way of mapping the meaning of a dataset to its structure. A dataset is messy or tidy depending on how rows, columns and tables are matched up with observations, variables and types. In tidy data: Each variable forms a column Each observation forms a row. Each type of observational unit forms a table."

  1. tweet_json_clean should be part of the twitter_archive_clean table

# function to remove link at the end of column text

def delete_link(x):
        link = x.find("http")
        if link == -1:
            x = x
        else:
            x = x[:link - 1]
        return x

#applying the remove link function to column text
twitter_archive_clean.text = twitter_archive_clean.text.apply(delete_link)

# Create wordcloud for names

# read names to be used in wordcloud
text=" ".join(str(review) for review in tweets['name'])

# Retrieve image from URL programatically 
url = "http://www.clker.com/cliparts/0/f/e/b/1433163706283394587dog%20silhoutte%20correct%20direction-md.png"

# mask the png image file 
dog_mask = np.array(Image.open(requests.get(url, stream=True).raw))

# Set and add stopwords
#  Exclude dog doe from appearing since it has the highest frequency in name
stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
stopwords.update(["dog", "doe"])

wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", mode="RGBA", max_words = 100, mask = dog_mask, stopwords=stopwords)

# generate word cloud
wc.generate(text)

#wordcloud in dog shape
plt.figure(figsize=[10,5])
plt.imshow(wc, interpolation="bilinear")
plt.axis("off")

# store to file
wc.to_file('wordcloud_name_dog_shape.png')

#Plot pie chart to show the neural network's confidence in its overall predictions
values = predictions['dog'].value_counts().head(50)
colors = ['lightskyblue', 'lightcoral']
labels = ['Predictions are True (Dogs)','Predictions are False (Not Dogs)']
explode = (0.1,0)

plt.pie(values,colors=colors,labels=labels,explode=explode,autopct='%1.1f%%', 
        counterclock=False, shadow=True, startangle=90)

plt.title('How Confident is the Neural Network in its Predictions?')

plt.axis('equal')  
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

Insight : How does the Neural Network fare - What are the Top 50 Predictions?¶

In essence, this analysis is based on the neural network's predictions labeled as True with the highest confidence.

In [351]:
# Create a df to segregate breed predictions that are true, from breed predictions that are false
#  Sort new df by the highest confidence and drop duplicate tweet_id
breeds = predictions.query("dog == True")
breeds= breeds.sort_values('confidence').drop_duplicates(['tweet_id'],keep='last').reset_index(drop=True)

# Store downloaded images based on url list in folder : top5fav
